  1. Install necessary dependencies: You need to install remove.bg by adding it to your package.json file.

```jsx
npm install -g remove.bg
```

2. Initialize `remove.bg` instance with some options for background processing and color filtering:

```javascript
// Remove.bg object
const img = document.querySelector('#remove-image');
remove.bg({
  url: 'url',
  filters: ['blur', 'brightness', 'contrast'], // specify the list of filters like `['blur', 'brightness']`
});
```

Replace `'url'` placeholder with whatever URL you want to apply.
For example:
```js
// Add blur filter as first argument
remove.bg({
  url: 'https://example.com/image.jpg?w=800',
  filters: [['blur', 'center', 50], ['brightness', 0.4]],
})
```

This will apply the blur filter applied by `blur()`, centering it at the location specified (for example, at an offset of 50 pixels), and adjust its brightness by 0.4.

Then you can get access to the filtered image:

```jsx
img.src = remove.bg(url)('.image').then((data) => data.src);
``` 

It returns a reference to the modified image which can be rendered or displayed further on page. Note that images may become darker if not properly filtered and adjusted.

Remember that you need to set the correct values for blur parameter based on the effect you want. For instance, try changing blur value from 0 to 200 with an eye for proper balance of white background.

